The Nyeri government has bought Sh4 million survey and mapping equipment from Germany.Lands executive Robert Thuo on Tuesday said the equipment will cut costs. The government had hired a consultancy firm to carry out surveys. The equipment will use modern technology to solve land disputes. The equipment being used previously was obsolete, he said.Thuo said more surveyors will be hired to map out 220 villages. Six of the villages have already been surveyed. The county is working to solve land disputes and plan towns, he said.Thuo said the modern equipment will fast-track the resolution of land disputes. A survey that previously took one week to be completed is now being done in half a day, he said.